{"id":"29d53709761d","content":"5 min read\nJust now\n\n--\n\nPress enter or click to view image in full size\n\nHi! If this is your first time here welcome! This is a series in which we dive into the accessibility side of frontend development from an engineers perspective. We’re working through common UI components to understand the building blocks that make them accessible from the start. And, if you’re a returning reader, welcome back! This week we’re going to be looking into form controls.\nForms are one of the most common places that users can interact with a website, from contact details to orders but they can also be one of the easiest places that can accidentally introduce accessibility barriers.\nA form that looks visually correct can still be difficult or impossible to use for different types of assistive technology such as screen readers, keyboard navigation, voice control software or cognitive accessibility tools.\nThe foundation of accessible forms is simple:\nEvery control needs a clear purpose, a clear name, and a clear state.\nIn this article we’ll cover the building blocks of accessible form controls:\n\n• text inputs\n\n• labels\n\n• checkboxes\n\n• radio groups\n\n• switches\n\n• helper text\n\n• required fields\n\n• grouping related controls with fieldset and legend\nText Inputs\nOne major flag that causes an accessibility issue is a text input without a label.\n<input type=\"text\" />Always provide an accessible name\nThe most common solution is a visible <label>.\n<label for=\"email\">\nEmail address\n</label>\n<input id=\"email\" type=\"email\" />The relationship is created through the matching attributes:\n\n• label for\n\n• matching input id\nNow assistive technology can announce:\n“Email address”\nAvoid placeholder-only labels\nA common pattern is:\n<input placeholder=\"Email address\" />This is not a replacement for a label.\nProblems:\n\n• disappears when the user starts typing\n\n• lower contrast\n\n• users with cognitive difficulties may forget the purpose\n\n• screen reader support varies\nUse placeholders for examples:\n<label for=\"postcode\">\nPostcode\n</label>\n<input id=\"postcode\" placeholder=\"Example: SR1 1AA\" />Another pattern that is accessible for inputs and other form controls is to nest the input within the label as this gives implicit association between the elements.\n<label class=\"field-container\">\n<span class=\"label-text\">\nEmail Address\n</span>\n<span class=\"hint\">\nWe will never share your email.\n</span> <input type=\"email\" name=\"email\">\n</label><label> Username <input type=\"text\" name=\"username\"> </label>\nWhile nesting is perfectly valid HTML, I generally prefer explicit for/id associations. As labels become more complex—with helper text, icons, or additional markup—the relationship is easier to understand, maintain and debug when it is explicit.\nCheckboxes\nCheckboxes represent independent choices.\n<label>\n<input type=\"checkbox\" />\nSubscribe to newsletter\n</label>The label wraps the input, creating the relationship automatically.\nAlternatively:\n<input id=\"terms\" type=\"checkbox\" />\n<label for=\"terms\">\nI agree to the terms and conditions\n</label>Checkbox groups\nWhen multiple checkboxes belong together, provide a group name.\n<fieldset>\n<legend>\nPreferred contact methods\n</legend> <label>\n<input type=\"checkbox\" />\nEmail\n</label>\n<label>\n<input type=\"checkbox\" />\nPhone\n</label>\n</fieldset>\nWith this pattern the inputs are grouped together using <fieldset> the <legend> acts as a label for the group. The user will now hear “Preferred contact methods, group” before reaching the checkboxes.\nRadio Groups\nRadio buttons represent a single choice from multiple options.\n<fieldset>\n<legend>\nAccount type\n</legend> <label>\n<input type=\"radio\" name=\"account\" value=\"personal\" />\nPersonal\n</label>\n<label>\n<input type=\"radio\" name=\"account\" value=\"business\" />\nBusiness\n</label>\n</fieldset>\nThe important parts of this pattern are\n\n• Same name: each of the inputs use the same name so this tells the browser that these controls belong together\n\n• Fieldset and legend: we’re using the fieldset and legend here again to group the inputs and give the group an accessible label\nSwitches\nSwitches are intended for toggling a setting or preference. Common examples include:\n\n• Enabling notifications\n\n• Switching between light and dark mode\n\n• Turning automatic updates on or off\nA switch represents a binary or boolean state — on/off or true/false.\n<button\nid=\"notifications-switch\"\nrole=\"switch\"\naria-checked=\"true\"\n>\nNotifications\n</button>const switchElement = document.getElementById(\"notifications-switch\");switchElement.addEventListener(\"click\", () => {\nconst isChecked =\nswitchElement.getAttribute(\"aria-checked\") === \"true\";\nswitchElement.setAttribute(\n\"aria-checked\",\nString(!isChecked)\n);\n});\nThe important parts are:\n\n• Accessible name → Notifications\n\n• Role → switch\n\n• State → aria-checked=\"true\" or aria-checked=\"false\"\nA screen reader should announce:\n“Notifications, switch, on”\nor\n“Notifications, switch, off”\nDon’t use switches for actions\nA switch changes the state of something.\nA button performs an action.\n\n• “Save changes” as a switch is incorrect\n\n• “Enable notifications” as a switch is correct\nHelper Text\nHelper text provides additional information:\nExamples:\n\n• formatting requirements\n\n• password rules\n\n• explanations\n<label for=\"password\">\nPassword\n</label>\n<input id=\"password\" aria-describedby=\"password-help\" />\n<p id=\"password-help\">\nMust contain at least 8 characters.\n</p>aria-describedby connects the additional information.\nA screen reader announces:\n“Password, edit text, Must contain at least 8 characters”\nRequired Fields\nRequired fields should communicate both visually and programmatically.\nVisual:\n<label>\nEmail address *\n</label>is not enough.\nThe asterisk has no meaning to assistive technology.\nUse:\n<input required />and make sure the label explains that is is required:\n<label>\nEmail address <span aria-hidden=\"true\">*</span>\n</label>Validation Messages\nErrors should be associated with the input.\n<input aria-invalid=\"true\" aria-describedby=\"email-error\" />\n<p id=\"email-error\">\nEnter a valid email address.\n</p>The user receives:\n\n• what is wrong\n\n• where it is wrong\n\n• how to fix it\nValidation should not rely on colour alone and error messages should appear at the point the error occurs, not just at the top of the page.\nGrouping Controls with Fieldset and Legend\nI know we’ve mentioned using fieldset and legend in the previous examples for checkboxes and for radios but fieldset and legend are often overlooked.\nThey are not just visual containers, they provide semantic relationships between the elements.\n<fieldset>\n<legend>\nDelivery address\n</legend> <label>\nStreet address\n</label>\n<input />\n<label>\nCity\n</label>\n<input />\n</fieldset>\nScreen readers announce the group name before users navigate through the controls, helping provide context for the fields that follow.\nKey take aways\nAccessible forms have a few core principles:\n\n• Every control has an accessible name\n\n• Labels are always associated with inputs using either explicit (for/id) or implicit (nested) labelling\n\n• Groups should have meaningful names and an accompanying legend\n\n• States are communicated programmatically\n\n• Helper text is connecting using relationships\n\n• Errors should be associated with the input and should explain what went wrong and how to fix it\nOne thing you’ll probably have noticed throughout this article — and hopefully throughout this series — is just how much accessibility comes for free when we lean on native HTML. Before reaching for ARIA or custom components, ask yourself whether a native element already provides the behaviour you need. More often than not, the browser has already solved the accessibility problem for you.\nAccessibility by Default is a series where I explore practical accessibility techniques from the perspective of a frontend engineer. Rather than repeating specifications, the goal is to explain the engineering decisions and patterns that make accessible interfaces easier to build from the start.\nYou can find the full series on my profile"}